  <!-- NUMBERS BEHIND THE DELAY -->
  <div class="section fade-scroll" id="delay">
    <div class="content">
      <h2>â€¢ Introduction / Background of the Study</h2>
      <p>
        This study investigates the statistical factors that contribute to the delayed completion of Junior High School (JHS) students at Diffun National High School. According to the 2024 Department of Education (DepEd) Basic Education Report, around 10% of public school students fail to finish JHS on time due to academic struggles (45%), financial difficulties (30%), and frequent absences (25%).  
        ðŸ”— <a href="https://www.deped.gov.ph" target="_blank">DepEd Basic Education Report 2024</a>
      </p>
      <p>The study aims to statistically determine which factorsâ€”attendance, academic performance, or socioeconomic statusâ€”most influence delayed completion.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="content">
      <h2>â€¢ Review of Related Literature</h2>
      <p><strong>1. Correlation Between Attendance and Academic Achievement</strong><br>
        Poor attendance directly lowers grades and is strongly linked to delayed school completion.  
        ðŸ”— <a href="https://eric.ed.gov/?id=EJ1254321" target="_blank">Effect of Class Attendance on Academic Performance</a>
      </p>
      <p><strong>2. Socioeconomic Status and School Retention</strong><br>
        Low socioeconomic status has been statistically linked to poor academic performance and late school completion.  
        ðŸ”— <a href="https://scholar.google.com/scholar_lookup?title=The+Impact+of+Socioeconomic+Status+on+Academic+Achievement&hl=en" target="_blank">View study</a>
      </p>
    </div>
    <div class="content">
